docs.abstract: Mr. Issa becomes one of the most prominent in a long list of Republican retirements, adding to talk of a Democratic wave in the midterm elections.
docs.snippet: Mr. Issa becomes one of the most prominent in a long list of Republican retirements, adding to talk of a Democratic wave in the midterm elections.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Representative Darrell Issa, whose hard-edge partisan attacks on President Barack Obama began softening as his district trended toward the Democrats, said on Wednesday that he would not seek re-election — the latest and one of the most prominent Republican retirements in the face of a potential Democratic wave.

headline.main: Darrell Issa, a California Republican, Will Not Seek Re-election to House
headline.print_headline: G.O.P. Is Losing Fierce Partisan in House

docs.abstract: Senators from both parties were scrambling for a new deal to reopen the government quickly, possibly just hours after the midnight deadline passed.
docs.snippet: Senators from both parties were scrambling for a new deal to reopen the government quickly, possibly just hours after the midnight deadline passed.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Much of the federal government officially shut down early Saturday morning after Senate Democrats, showing remarkable solidarity in the face of a clear political danger, blocked consideration of a stopgap spending measure to keep the government operating.

headline.main: Government Shutdown Begins as Budget Talks Falter in Senate
headline.print_headline: Shutdown Begins as Budget Talks Falter in Senate

byline.original: By Sheryl Gay Stolberg and Thomas Kaplan

docs.abstract: The successful vote in the House provided only a faint glimmer of hope that a crisis could be averted before government funding expires at midnight on Friday.
docs.snippet: The successful vote in the House provided only a faint glimmer of hope that a crisis could be averted before government funding expires at midnight on Friday.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The House approved a stopgap spending bill on Thursday night to keep the government open past Friday, but Senate Democrats — angered by President Trump’s vulgar aspersions and a lack of progress on a broader budget and immigration deal — appeared ready to block the measure.

headline.main: House Passes Short-Term Spending Bill, Setting Up Shutdown Battle in Senate
headline.print_headline: Senate Showdown Looms As Spending Bill Advances

byline.original: By Thomas Kaplan and Sheryl Gay Stolberg

docs.abstract: President Trump’s third attempt to impose restrictions on travel from predominantly Muslim nations will face a test in the Supreme Court this spring.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s third attempt to impose restrictions on travel from predominantly Muslim nations will face a test in the Supreme Court this spring.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court announced on Friday that it would consider a challenge to President Trump’s latest effort to limit travel from countries said to pose a threat to the nation’s security, adding a major test of presidential power to a docket already crowded with blockbusters.

headline.main: Supreme Court to Consider Challenge to Trump’s Latest Travel Ban
headline.print_headline: Supreme Court Will Hear  New Travel Ban Challenge

docs.abstract: In an interview, Senator Richard J. Durbin says President Trump’s private immigration comments shed new light on his policy motivations.
docs.snippet: In an interview, Senator Richard J. Durbin says President Trump’s private immigration comments shed new light on his policy motivations.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As they departed the now famous Oval Office meeting where President Trump used vulgar language to disparage the national origin of some potential immigrants, Senators Lindsey Graham and Richard J. Durbin found themselves in a condition unfamiliar to such veteran politicians: speechless.

headline.main: Inside the Oval Office Immigration Meeting That Left a Senator Stunned
headline.print_headline: Comments in Meeting Shed Light on Trump’s Motivations, Durbin Says

docs.abstract: Mr. Hatch, the longest-serving Senate Republican, announced that he would retire at the end of the year, clearing a path for Mitt Romney to run.
docs.snippet: Mr. Hatch, the longest-serving Senate Republican, announced that he would retire at the end of the year, clearing a path for Mitt Romney to run.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Orrin G. Hatch of Utah, the longest-serving Senate Republican, announced Tuesday that he would retire at the end of the year, rebuffing personal pleas from President Trump to seek an eighth term and paving the way for Mitt Romney, a critic of Mr. Trump’s, to run for the seat.

headline.main: Orrin Hatch, Utah Senator, to Retire, Opening Path for Mitt Romney
headline.print_headline: Hatch to Retire, Opening a Seat  For Trump Critic Romney to Seek

docs.abstract: The first congressional criminal referral in connection with Russian meddling targeted a former British spy, not anyone accused of conspiracy.
docs.snippet: The first congressional criminal referral in connection with Russian meddling targeted a former British spy, not anyone accused of conspiracy.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — More than a year after Republican leaders promised to investigate Russian interference in the presidential election, two influential Republicans on Friday made the first known congressional criminal referral in connection with the meddling — against one of the people who sought to expose it.

headline.main: Republican Senators Raise Possible Charges Against Author of Trump Dossier
headline.print_headline: G.O.P. Senators Pursuing Author Of File on Trump

docs.lead_paragraph: The political news cycle is fast, and keeping up can be overwhelming. Trying to find differing perspectives worth your time is even harder. That’s why we have scoured the internet for political writing from the right and left that you might not have seen.

headline.main: Right and Left React to the Clash Between Trump and Bannon

docs.abstract: Despite signing an order to keep the prison at Guantánamo Bay, Cuba, open, President Trump hasn’t solved problems that kept him from bringing new detainees there last year.
docs.snippet: Despite signing an order to keep the prison at Guantánamo Bay, Cuba, open, President Trump hasn’t solved problems that kept him from bringing new detainees there last year.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump announced Tuesday in his State of the Union address that he had signed an executive order to keep the Guantánamo Bay wartime prison open, he ad-libbed a line that was not in his staff-vetted prepared remarks, declaring that “in many cases,” terrorism detainees who are captured in the future will now be sent there.

headline.main: Ordering Guantánamo to Stay Open Is One Thing, but Refilling It Is Another
headline.print_headline: Guantánamo Pledge Is Difficult to Keep
